Overview

In week 07 of the course, we introduced linear basis function models via splines. This report goes into splines in a little more detail, primarily around with the spline basis. If you are interested to learn more about how the spline basis is constructed, please see Section 7.4 of the Introduction to Statistical Learning.

Synthetic data

Inputs

As discussed in lecture, the spline basis is constructed relative to the input and not the response. We will use synthetic data to show that is indeed the case. We will be interested in modeling a sine wave, but we will use data generated from two different assumptions. In the first data set, 51 evenly spaced points between \(-\pi\) and \(+\pi\) are used. The second data set will have 51 randomly generated input values based on a normal distribution with mean 0 and standard deviation \(\frac{\pi}{3}\). Can you figure out why this particular standard deviation was selected?

The two different input vectors are created in the code chunk below.

x_even <- seq(-pi, pi, length.out = 51)

set.seed(61231)
x_norm <- rnorm(n = 51, mean = 0, sd = pi/3)

The two different input sets are compared below using a number line. Notice that the randomly generated data point are âbunchedâ together around the mean value of 0.

tibble::tibble(x_even = x_even,
               x_norm = x_norm) %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column() %>% 
  tidyr::gather(key = "key", value = "value", -rowid) %>% 
  tidyr::separate(key,
                  c("x_ltr", "type"),
                  sep = "_") %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = value, y = 0)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = type,
                           shape = type),
             size = 3) +
  ggthemes::scale_color_colorblind("") +
  scale_shape_manual("",
                     values = c("even" = 3,
                                "norm" = 5)) +
  labs(y = "", x = "x") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.y = element_blank())

Natural spline basis

Letâs start out by generating a natural spline basis with 4 degrees-of-freedom. We can accomplish this with the model.matrix() and the splines::ns() functions. This approach mirrors using the lm() function to fit a spline model. Instead, we will go through the slightly more tedious approach of first generating the basis and then applying that basis to a data set.

We will start out by placing both the evenly spaced and randomly generated datasets into separate data.frames.

even_df <- tibble::tibble(x = x_even)

norm_df <- tibble::tibble(x = x_norm)

Next, we will create the natural spline basis with 4 degrees-of-freedom using the evenly spaced data set. The str() function is used to display the âstructureâ of the basis_even_04 object to the screen. Notice that the object has multiple attributes, one of which is referred to as the "knots". The knots are interior input values or âlocationsâ that are used to define the simple polynomials that will construct the basis. It might seem a little confusing, but the attributes provide a lot of information about the basis. The knots themselves are labeled or named to be "25%", "50%", and "75%". This denotes that they correspond to the 0.25, 0.5, and 0.75 quantiles of the 51 evenly spaced x values. The "Boundary.knots" attribute provides the boundary values of the variable. As shown in the print out below, the boundary values are displayed to be -3.14 and 3.14, which corresponds to the bounds of the evenly spaced variable between \(-\pi\) and \(\pi\).

basis_even_04 <- splines::ns(even_df$x, df = 4)

The data type of class() of the basis_even_04 object is shown below. It is a "ns" object, but is also considered to be a "matrix". As shown in the str() result, the dimensionality of the object is 51 rows by 4 columns. Each column corresponds to a different curve associated with the basis. You can think of these columns as the features we are interested in studying in a model.

class(basis_even_04)

The basis result contains almost everything we need from a modeling perspective. However, we will extract the knots and use those directly to create the design basis matrix associated with the natural spline with 4 degrees-of-freedom. The knots are extracts and assigned to the variable knots_use_even_04 in the code chunk below.

knots_use_even_04 <- as.vector(attributes(basis_even_04)$knots)

Now letâs go ahead and create the complete design basis matrix. In lecture we referred to basis design matrices as \(\boldsymbol{\Phi}\)-matrices. However in this report, we will denote them with captial Xâs. The model.matrix() is used in conjuction with splines::ns() again, but this time the basis is defined with the knots argument, rather than the df argument. This forces the natural spline basis to be created based upon the specific x values associated with the knots. After the Xmat_even_04 design matrix is created the first few rows of the matrix are printed to the screen.

Xmat_even_04 <- model.matrix( ~ splines::ns(x, knots = knots_use_even_04), data = even_df)

Each basis column or feature corresponds to a different polynomial curve. The features can be plotted with respect to the input x which helps us interpret what the features represent. To slow and tedious way to do this with ggplot2 is to use a separate geom_line() call for each feature, as shown in the code chunk below.

even_df %>% 
  bind_cols(Xmat_even_04 %>% as.data.frame() %>% tbl_df()) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(y = s_01)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(y = s_02)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(y = s_03)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(y = s_04)) +

The âggplot-wayâ to create this figure though is to reshape the design matrix from a âwideâ to a âlongâ format. The âlongâ format will have fewer columns than the wide, with one variable storing the name of the feature and another column for the value of the feature. At first it might seem odd to structure the data in this manner, but long-formats can be quite useful, especially in working with time-series applications. The code chunk below shows how to merge the input with the design matrix and then reformat using the tidyr::gather() function. Think of âgatheringâ as âpullingâ together many of the columns into a smaller number of columns. The new key column denotes the original variable names and the new value column is the value of the original variable. Any variables we do not wish to âgatherâ together can be listed with - before their names within the tidyr::gather() call. The âgatheredâ data set is stored to the object even_basis_04_lf. The glimpse() of the object is printed to the screen to show the dimensions and the names of the variables. The (Intercept) column was removed from the design matrix before the reformating to long-format. The intercept column is just a column of 1âs, so we will ignore it for plotting purposes.

even_basis_04_lf <- even_df %>% 
  bind_cols(Xmat_even_04 %>% 
              as.data.frame() %>% 
              tbl_df()) %>% 
  select(-`(Intercept)`) %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column() %>% 
  tidyr::gather(key = "feature_name",
                value = "feature_value",
                -rowid, -x)

Each column in Xmat_even_04 (minus the intercept column) is represented in the above figure. The first spline feature is a parabolic like centered at 0. The second and third features are sinusoidal-like. The second feature takes on negative values when the input is less than about -0.5, while the third feature is always positive. The fourth feature is a more complex looking curve which is positive near the upper bound of the input space.

We will sum together the 4 features of this spline basis to try and approximate a function. Consider the input value of x=1, denoted by a vertical dashed red line in the graph below. If we would just sum together the 4 features at x=1, the first three features would be added together, while the fourth feature would be subtracted from their sum because it is a slightly negative value.

even_basis_04_lf %>%

If we would sum together all of the features at x=2, all four curves would be added together since all four curves are positive numbers at that input value. The figure below denotes the x=2 location, similar to the previous figure.

even_basis_04_lf %>%

  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, color = "grey50") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 2, color = "red", linetype = "dashed",

We can sum together the four features at each of the input locations. The code chunk below does that a group_by() and subsequent mutate() operation to create teh sum_features variable. The sum of the four feature is plotted as a red curve in the figure below. Notice how the summed value follows the first feature until about x=-1. This represents that the other three features cancel out. After than point the summed value increases until it begins to saturate at 1 by x=1. Once the summed value saturates, the features are balancing out as they each continue to change as the input changes.

even_basis_04_lf %>% 
  group_by(rowid, x) %>% 
  mutate(sum_features = sum(feature_value)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = feature_value)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, color = "grey50") +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = feature_name),
            size = 1.15) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = feature_name),
             size = 2) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(y = sum_features),
            color = "red", size = 1.15) +
  ggthemes::scale_color_colorblind() +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

If we were to simply sum together the four features from this particular spline basis, all we could approximate would be the s-type curve plotted in red. The intercept would allow us to shift that curve up and down, but clearly the spline basis would have limited use. Splines are however quite flexible. The reason for that is because we are not simply summing together the features. Rather, we will use a weighted sum. Those weights are the coefficients of a linear model!

To see that explicitely, letâs define each feature of the spline basis as \(s_{j}\left(x\right)\). The \(n\)-th observationâs mean trend using the 4 degrees-of-freedom nature spline basis is equal to:

\[ \mu_n = \beta_0 + \beta_1 s_{1}\left(x_n\right) + \beta_2 s_{2}\left(x_n\right) + \beta_3 s_{3}\left(x_n\right) + \beta_4 s_{4}\left(x_n\right) \]

Or, written in summation notation by summing over \(j=0\) (the intercept, \(s_0\left(x\right) = 1\)) up to the \(J\)-th basis feature:

\[ \mu_n = \sum_{j=0}^{J} \left( \beta_j s_j\left(x_n\right)\right) \]

Fitting the model requires learning the \(J+1\) \(\boldsymbol{\beta}\)-parameters, just like a linear model consisting of simple additive linear relationships!

Before discussing the fitting procedure though, letâs now see what happens to our basis with the same degrees of freedom if we change the input âlocationsâ. colnames(Xmat_norm_04) <- c(colnames(Xmat_norm_04)[1], sprintf("s_%02d", 1:ncol(basis_norm_04)))

The spline degrees-of-freedom denote a particular set of feature shapes. The data points impact the specific details of those shapes, but the shapes themselves are governed by the degrees-of-freedom. Thus, if we want to try out different shapes, we need to try out a spline with a different level of complexity.

The code chunk below uses model.matrix() directly to create the basis design matrix associated splines with 8 degrees-of-freedom for both data sets.

Xmat_norm_08 <- model.matrix( ~ splines::ns(x, df = 8), data = norm_df)

Now, do the differences between the data sets matter? Well, the configuration of the inputs and thus the design matrix can impact the interpretation of the results. Remember that the posterior covariance between the \(\boldsymbol{\beta}\) parameters is related to the design matrix sum-of-squares matrix:

\[ \mathrm{cov}\left(\boldsymbol{\beta}, \boldsymbol{\beta}\right) \propto \left( \mathbf{X}^T\mathbf{X} \right)^{-1} \]

Letâs calculate the inverse of the sum-of-squares matrix for 4 degrees-of-freedom splines associated with both data sets.

inv_ssmat_even_04 <- solve(t(Xmat_even_04) %*% Xmat_even_04)

inv_ssmat_norm_04 <- solve(t(Xmat_norm_04) %*% Xmat_norm_04)

These matrices represent the covariance between the parameters, so we can convert them to correlation matrices to get an idea about how correlated the parameters will be.

cov2cor(inv_ssmat_even_04)
##             (Intercept)        s_01        s_02         s_03         s_04
## (Intercept)  1.00000000 -0.51830781 -0.55347404 -0.919155651 -0.030598256
## s_01        -0.51830781  1.00000000 -0.05590832  0.308444906  0.427411629
## s_02        -0.55347404 -0.05590832  1.00000000  0.530896978 -0.363432824
## s_03        -0.91915565  0.30844491  0.53089698  1.000000000 -0.002482579
## s_04        -0.03059826  0.42741163 -0.36343282 -0.002482579  1.000000000
cov2cor(inv_ssmat_norm_04)
##             (Intercept)       s_01        s_02       s_03        s_04

Since the print out can be a little difficult to read, letâs visualize the correlation matrices with corrplot. The posterior correlation matrix for the evenly spaced points is shown below. Notice that the highest correlation is between the intercept and the 3rd basis feature, at -0.92.

cov2cor(inv_ssmat_even_04) %>% 
  corrplot::corrplot(type = "upper", method = "number")

The posterior correlation matrix for the randomly generated inputs is shown below. We can see that the intercept is also highly anti-correlated with the 3rd basis feature, but the intercept is also highly anti-correlated with the first basis feature!

cov2cor(inv_ssmat_norm_04) %>% 
  corrplot::corrplot(type = "upper", method = "number")

The input âconfigurationâ impacts the interpretation of the model fitting results. However, with splines we are less interested in intepreting the basis âeffectsâ and more interested in smoothing non-linear trends. To that end, letâs apply the natural spline basis to the a modeling task.

Sine-wave output

Letâs take the evenly spaced data points and generate noisy observations around a sine-wave. The likelihood noise, \(\sigma\), will be set to be 0.15.

set.seed(51231)
even_data <- even_df %>% 
  mutate(mu = sin(x),
         y = rnorm(n = n(), mean = mu, sd = 0.15))

The noisy inputs are plotted relative to the true sine-wave in the figure below.

even_data %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x)) +
  stat_function(fun = sin,
                color = "black") +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(y = y),
             color = "red") +
  theme_bw()

We could fit a Bayesian linear model using the framework introduced in lecture. However, letâs just get some ideas about the behavior of the approach. So we will use non-Bayesian techniques in this report. Itâs straight forward to fit a non-Bayesian linear model with a spline basis to these noisy observations. We already saw what the basis functions look like, so we will fit the model directly with the lm() function. We can use the formula interface to specify the spline basis directly to the linear model.

fit_even_04_sine <- lm(y ~ splines::ns(x, df = 4), data = even_data)

The summary of the spline model fit is printed below.

fit_even_04_sine %>% summary()

Letâs take a look at closer look at the coefficients and their confidence intervals with coefplot(). As shown below, the coefficient acting on the second basis feature is slightly over 2. The coefficient acting on the first basis feature is basically zero. The coefficient acting on the third basis feature is less than -0.5, and the coefficient acting on the fourth basis feature is about 3/4. Thus, when we considered summing together the 4 features the first feature will get very little weight in order to approximate the sine wave, compared with the other features.

coefplot::coefplot(fit_even_04_sine) + theme_bw()

Letâs show that is indeed the case by overlaying the weighted sum of the 4 features with the basis features themselves. The code chunk below organizes the coefficients into a data.frame for the feature weights. Then merges that with the long-format feature object even_basis_04_lf. This allows directly comparing the non-weighted summed features with the weighted sum of the features. Note that, we are focused on the summation excluding the intercept just to be consistent with the figures from the beginning of the report. The non-weighted sum of the four features is still shown by the red curve. The weighted sum, based on the coefficients from the fit linear model, is displayed by the navy blue curve. The weights now change how the 4 features are summed together, producing a curve that looks like a sine wave, rather than the s-shaped red curve.

weights_even_04_sine <- tibble::tibble(
  w = as.vector(coef(fit_even_04_sine)[-1])
) %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column("feature_id") %>% 
  mutate(feature_name = sprintf("s_%02d", feature_id))

even_basis_04_lf %>% 
  left_join(weights_even_04_sine %>% 
              select(w, feature_name),
            by = "feature_name") %>% 
  group_by(rowid, x) %>% 
  mutate(sum_features = sum(feature_value),
         weight_sum = sum(w * feature_value)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = feature_value)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, color = "grey50") +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = feature_name),
            size = 1.15) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = feature_name),
             size = 2) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(y = sum_features),
            color = "red", size = 1.15) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(y = weight_sum),
            color = "navyblue", size = 1.15) +
  ggthemes::scale_color_colorblind() +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

Cosine-wave output

The benefit of splines are the flexibility of the basis to easily adapt to different outputs. We can apply the same basis to a different function. Fitting the model to a different data set, and thus relearning the weights applied to each basis feature changes how the features are summed together. Letâs demonstrate this by generating noisy observations of a cosine wave.

set.seed(51231)
even_data_cos <- even_df %>% 
  mutate(mu = cos(x),
         y = rnorm(n = n(), mean = mu, sd = 0.15))

The evenly spaced input values were used, but by using the cosine instead of the sine the data are different from before.

even_data_cos %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x)) +
  stat_function(fun = cos,
                color = "black") +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(y = y),
             color = "red") +
  theme_bw()

Fitting the non-Bayesian model is again straight forward to do, We can reuse the same formula. We just need to change the data!

fit_even_04_cos <- lm(y ~ splines::ns(x, df = 4), data = even_data_cos)

Inspecting the coefficients of the model reveals that none of the features are now essentially zero. The first feature now has the largest absolute value, with a coefficient of nearly 3.

coefplot::coefplot(fit_even_04_cos) + theme_bw()

Letâs now apply the learned maximum likelihood estimate (MLE) coefficient values to the 4 basis features again and compare to the non-weighted sum. The weighted sum of the 4 basis features is shown by the blue curve in the graph below. Again this figure neglects the intercept, which would shift the blue curve down if applied. By using different coefficient values, we have altered the result of the weighted sum of the 4 features compared to what we had last time!

weights_even_04_cos <- tibble::tibble(
  w = as.vector(coef(fit_even_04_cos)[-1])
) %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column("feature_id") %>% 
  mutate(feature_name = sprintf("s_%02d", feature_id))

even_basis_04_lf %>% 
  left_join(weights_even_04_cos %>% 
              select(w, feature_name),
            by = "feature_name") %>% 
  group_by(rowid, x) %>% 
  mutate(sum_features = sum(feature_value),
         weight_sum = sum(w * feature_value)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = feature_value)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, color = "grey50") +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = feature_name),
            size = 1.15) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = feature_name),
             size = 2) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(y = sum_features),
            color = "red", size = 1.15) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(y = weight_sum),
            color = "navyblue", size = 1.15) +
  ggthemes::scale_color_colorblind() +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")
